It is impossible without further proof to assume that the villainous misleader of youth who is described to us in the report of the above commission, as encouraging a young man to defraud the Crown by means of pet-jury, in order that he may purchase his lands from him at a nominal price, can be identical with the grave moralist of the Speculum Hominis· and the Vox clamantis. Gower humbly confoeses that he has been a great sinuer, but he does not spaek in the tone of a converted libertine: we cannot reconcile our idea of him with the proceedings of the disreputable chmcter who for his own ends encouraged the young William Septvans in his dishonesty and exnavagance. The two men apparently bore the same armS, and therefore they belonged to the same family, but beyond this we cannot go. It may be observed moreover that the picture suggested to Prof. Morley by the deed of 1373, executed at Otsord, of the poet’s residence in the pleasant valley of the Darent, which he describes at some length-¹, m'ust in any case be dismissed as baseless. Otford was a maner held by Sir John Cobharn ⁸, and whether the John Gower of this deed be the poet or no, it is pretty clear that the deod in question was executed there principally for this reason, and not beoeuse it was the residence of John Gower.
